OpenStreetMap Project Data Wrangling with MongoDB

Mofei Li

February 26, 2015

Map Area: Portland, Oregon, United States

https://www.openstreetmap.org/relation/186579
http://metro.teczno.com/#portland

1. Problems Encountered in the Map and the Solution Code for Data Wrangling and Reshaping

  • Over-abbreviated street types (“Ave.”, “Dr”)
  • Letters within zipcodes (‘OR 97214’, ‘Portland, OR 97209’)
  • Inconsistent or incorrect states (‘Oregon’, ‘Or’, ‘oregon’, ‘1401 N.E. 68th Avenue Portland, OR 97213’, ‘CA’, ‘Washington’, ‘97222’, ‘Wa’)
  • Inconsistent cities (‘PORTLAND’, ‘Porland’, ‘Portland’, ‘Portland’, ‘Portland, OR’)
  • Inconsistent cuisines (“vietnamese;sandwich”, “sub_sandwiches”, “sandwich”)
#!/usr/bin/env python
# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-
import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET
import pprint
import re
import codecs
import json


### street type search
street_type_re = re.compile(r'\b\S+\.?$', re.IGNORECASE) 
### zipcode search
zipcode_re = re.compile(r'[^0-9\-]', re.IGNORECASE) 
### state name search, for Oregon
state_OR_re = re.compile(r'.+Portland.+|Or.*|.+Street|97222|oregon') 
### state name search, for Washington
state_WA_re = re.compile(r'Wa.*')
### city name search, for Portland
city_portland_re = re.compile(r'[Pp]ortland') 
### city name search, for cities other than Portland
city_other_re = re.compile(r',\sOR$')

CREATED = [ "version", "changeset", "timestamp", "user", "uid"]

### expected street type
expected = ["Avenue", "Boulevard", "Broadway", "Circle", "Court", "Drive", \
            "Highway", "Lane", "Parkway", "Place", "Road", "Street", "Terrace", "Way"]

### street type conversion dictionary
mapping = { 'St'     : 'Street',
            'St.'    : 'Street',
            'street' : 'Street',
            'Street,': 'Street',
            'Rd'     : "Road",
            'Rd.'    : 'Road',
            'ROAD'   : 'Road',
            'road'   : 'Road',
            'Pkwy'   : 'Parkway',
            'Pky'    : 'Parkway',
            'Ln'     : 'Lane',
            'Hwy'    : 'Highway',
            'Dr'     : 'Drive',
            'Dr.'    : 'Drive',
            'Cir'    : 'Circle',
            'Blvd'   : 'Boulevard',
            'Blvd.'  : 'Boulevard',
            'ave'    : 'Avenue',
            'Ave'    : 'Avenue',
            'Ave.'   : 'Avenue' }

### function for reshaping and auditting the whole dataset
def shape_element(element):
    if element.tag == "node" or element.tag == "way" :
        node = {}
        node["created"] = {}
        node["type"] = element.tag
        for babytree in element.getchildren():
            if babytree.tag == "tag":
                #if "address" not in node.keys():
                    #node['address'] = {}    
                if re.search("^addr\:.+$",babytree.attrib['k']):
                    if "address" not in node.keys():
                        node['address'] = {}
                    match = re.search("\w+$",babytree.attrib['k'])
                    field = match.group()
                    if field == 'street':
                        street_name = babytree.attrib['v']
                        m1 = street_type_re.search(street_name)
                        if m1:
                            street_type = m1.group() #The 'word' of the street_name
                            if street_type not in expected and street_type in mapping.keys():
                                street_name = re.sub(street_type, mapping[street_type], street_name)
                        node["address"][field] = street_name
                    elif field == 'postcode':
                        zipcode = babytree.attrib['v']
                        m2 = zipcode_re.search(zipcode)
                        if m2:
                            #Remove any character(or space) other than number and "-"
                            zipcode = re.sub(r'([^0-9\-])', '', zipcode) 
                        node["address"][field] = zipcode
                    elif field == 'state':
                        state = babytree.attrib['v']
                        m31 = state_OR_re.search(state)
                        m32 = state_WA_re.search(state)
                        if m31:
                            # Fix the weird state name that should be 'OR'
                            state = re.sub(r'.+Portland.+|Or.*|.+Street|97222|oregon', 'OR', state)
                            node["address"][field] = state
                        elif m32:
                            # Fix the weird state name that should be 'WA'
                            state = re.sub(r'Wa.*', 'WA', state)
                        node["address"][field] = state
                    elif field == 'city':
                        city = babytree.attrib['v']
                        m41 = city_portland_re.search(city)
                        m42 = city_other_re.search(city)
                        if m41: #Search if thers's 'portland' or 'Portland' in the string
                            node["address"][field] = 'Portland'
                        elif m42:
                            # If the city name is ended with ', OR', then remove it
                            city = re.sub(r',\sOR$', '', city)
                        node["address"][field] = city
                        
                    else:
                        node["address"][field] = babytree.attrib['v']

                else: 
                    node[babytree.attrib['k']] = babytree.attrib['v']

        for attrib in element.attrib:
            if attrib not in CREATED:
                node[attrib] = element.attrib[attrib]
            else:
                node["created"][attrib] = element.attrib[attrib]
        if element.tag == "node":
            node["pos"] = [element.attrib["lat"], element.attrib["lon"]]
        else:
            node["node_refs"] = []
            for tag in element.iter("nd"):
                node["node_refs"].append(tag.attrib['ref'])
        return node
    else:
        return None

    
### function for writing the cleaned data into a json file    
def process_map(file_in, pretty = False):
    # You do not need to change this file
    file_out = "{0}.json".format(file_in)
    data = []
    with codecs.open(file_out, "w") as fo:
        for _, element in ET.iterparse(file_in):
            el = shape_element(element)
            if el:
                data.append(el)
                if pretty:
                    fo.write(json.dumps(el, indent=2)+"\n")
                else:
                    fo.write(json.dumps(el) + "\n")
    return data

1.1 Street Type

Just as what we see in the example of video letures, some of the street types (the last word in the addr:street attribute) are abbreviated (like ‘Cir’, ‘Dr’ etc) and some with punctuation at the end (like ‘Street,’). So I updated all the problematic street types (such as: ‘Pkwy’ ==> ‘Parkway’, ‘Hwy’ ==> ‘Highway’). Moreover, I found one really funny one – ‘poop’!

Find out more about the node ‘poop’

1.2 Zip Code

For the zip code part, the data is much cleaner than the address. I only found a few bad records – they are ‘OR 97214’, ‘OR’, ‘Milwaukie, OR 97267’, ‘NE 37th Ave’, ‘Portland, OR 97209’ and ‘OR 97006’. So I removed all the characters in the zip code string.
There’s another thing that out of my expectation is that besides the majority of zip codes start with ‘97’, which is all the zip codes in Oregon should do, some others start with ‘98’. And according to information on the Zip code page of wikipedia, starting with ‘98’ indicates that it is a place of the State of Washington. Then I did some research and found the concept of ‘Portland metropolitan area’. According to wikipedia, The Portland metropolitan area or Greater Portland is a metropolitan area in the U.S. states of Oregon and Washington centered on the principal city of Portland, Oregon. So ‘98’ zip codes are not problematic in this case. But not until then I didn’t realize that the osm file I download from Mapzen was not bounded as the city of Portland but the Portland metropolitan area.
The good news is all the other records are consistent with the zip code system: with 5-digit zip code and optionally end with hyphen and 4-digit zoning number.

1.3 State

Here are all the unique results I got from auditing addr:state from the raw data: ‘1401 N.E. 68th Avenue Portland, OR 97213’, ‘WA’, ‘Southwest Morrison Street’, ‘CA’, ‘Washington’, ‘Oregon’, ‘Or’, ‘oregon’, ‘97222’, ‘Wa’, ‘OR’. So I harmonized ‘Oregon’, ‘Or’, ‘oregon’ into ‘OR’ and ‘Washington’ and ‘Wa’ into ‘WA’. ‘1401 N.E. 68th Avenue Portland, OR 97213’ and ‘Southwest Morrison Street’ are two street addresses from Portland and ‘97222’ is a zip code of Portland, so they were also changed into ‘OR’. Unexpectedly, I found one ‘CA’ in the dataset. I assumed that it is a typo of ‘WA’ and let’s find out if my assumption’s right in the mongo shell.

db.portland.findOne( {"address.state" : "CA" }, {"address" : 1} )
{
    "_id" : ObjectId("54d91f2f5d82f275c87183b3"),
    "address" : {
        "city" : "Portland",
        "state" : "CA",
        "street" : "Northeast 10th Avenue",
        "housenumber" : "1530",
        "postcode" : "97232"
    }
}

The post turned out to be a street in Portland, so I updated the state information to ‘OR’.

db.portland.update( 
    { "address.state" : "CA" }, 
    { $set : {"address.state" : "OR"} },  
    { multi : true} )
WriteResult({ "nMatched" : 1, "nUpserted" : 0, "nModified" : 1 })

1.4 City

The city information is highly inconsistent. For example, I found nine kinds of ‘Portland’ in the dataset – they are ‘PORTLAND’, ‘Porland’, ‘Portland’, ‘Portland’, ‘Portland, OR’, ‘Portland, Oregon’, ‘Portland, Oregon’, ‘portland’ and ‘portland, Oregon’ – with/without the extra space, with/without the state name, also different capitalizations. The similar situation happens with the name of other cities. So I standardized the all of city names by removing the possible state names and extra space in the end, also forced all the first letters to be upper case.

1.5 Cuisine

For the cuisine strings, I first forced all the letters to be lower case.

db.portland.find({cuisine : {$exists : 1}}).forEach(
  function(e) {
    e.cuisine = e.cuisine.toLowerCase();
    db.portland.save(e);
  }
)

Then splited strings into vectors by semicolon, for example: “vietnamese;sandwich” ==> [“vietnamese”, “sandwich”]. Finally, harmonized the less common names, for example: “sub_sandwiches” ==> “sandwich”, “coffee” ==> “coffee_shop” etc.

Top one contributing user

db.portland.aggregate( [
    { $group : {"_id" : "$created.user", 
                "count" : { "$sum" : 1} } },
    { $sort : {"count" : -1} }, 
    { $limit : 1 } ] )

Number of users appearing only once (having one post)

db.portland.aggregate( [
    { $group : {"_id" : "$created.user", 
                "count" : { "$sum" : 1} } },
    { $group : {"_id" : "$count",
                "num_users": { "$sum" : 1} } },
    { $sort : {"_id" : 1} },
    { $limit : 1} ] )
{ "_id" : 1, "num_users" : 198 }

Posts for different states
# How many posts are of WA and how many of OR?
The Portland Metropolitan area consists of five cities (Portland, Gresham, Hillsboro and Beaverton) , four in Oregon and one (Vancouver) in Washington. I want to find out the ratio of posts related to OR and WA seperately.
Since there are both address.state and address.postcode available that can help us easily identify the states, first let’s see which information should we use.

db.portland.find({ "address.postcode" : { $exists : 1} }).count()
50698
db.portland.find({ "address.state" : { $exists : 1} }).count()
12929

There are far more address.postcode records available. Let’s stick with it to explore more information related to different regions. As I mentioned before, postcodes in Oregon and Washington start with ‘97’ and ‘98’, respectively.

db.portland.find( {"address.postcode" : { $regex : "^98.+"} } ).count()
296
db.portland.find( {"address.postcode" : { $regex : "^97.+"} } ).count()
50399
  • Only 0.5% of the posts with address.postcode available are in WA. It seemed superisingly small to me at first, but then I found the area of Vancouver - 49.86 sq mi - only takes 0.75% of the area of Portland Metropolitan Area (6,684 sq. mi). So the result seems reasonable now.
